Creating Launchers
******************

Desktop Application Integration
================================

kitty-launcher can create .desktop files that integrate with your desktop
environment's application menu. This allows you to launch sessions directly
from your system menu without opening a terminal.


Using the --create-launcher Command
====================================

To create a launcher for a session:

   kitty-launcher --create-launcher <LAUNCHER_NAME> <SESSION_NAME>

This command will:

   1. Create ~/.local/share/applications/ directory if it doesn't exist
   2. Generate a .desktop file named kitty-launcher-<LAUNCHER_NAME>.desktop
   3. Register the launcher in your desktop environment


Example: Creating a Launcher
=============================

To create a launcher named "dev-env" for the "dev" session:

   kitty-launcher --create-launcher dev-env dev

This creates: ~/.local/share/applications/kitty-launcher-dev-env.desktop




Desktop Environment Refresh
============================

After creating or installing launchers, you may need to refresh your desktop
environment for the changes to take effect. Common methods:

   • Log out and log back in
   • Press Alt+F2 and type 'r' (KDE Plasma)
   • Press Super key and search again (GNOME)
   • Manually update your application menu cache

Desktop Entry Files
===================

The .desktop files created follow the FreeDesktop.org Desktop Entry specification.
You can manually edit files at: ~/.local/share/applications/

Example .desktop file structure:

   [Desktop Entry]
   Type=Application
   Name=Launcher Name
   Comment=Launcher Description
   Exec=kitty-launcher session-name
   Icon=kitty
   Categories=System;TerminalEmulator;


